title: Six Sentence Sunday
body:
(only a bit late, as it often is…)

After reading that part, Sansa put the journal down and stared at the ring in her left index finger. It was unremarkable enough: a wide silver ring with a stylised wolf’s head with crudely formed ears, eyes and nose. When she circled it around her finger she realised she had never questioned its presence even though all her other belongings, including clothes and the earrings she had been wearing that day in the Red Keep, had vanished.

All but this ring… She had received it as a birthday present from her parents not long after their visit to Winterfell, where Sansa had first experienced that strange feeling in Sansa’s chamber, and after which she had become interested in the history of her family. Her parents told her they had bought the ring from an antique shop in Wintertown, and the owner had assured them that it was a genuine article: the kind of ring typical to the members of House Stark as a recognition of the sigil of their house, a direwolf.

(Source for the ring ‘Taigakoru’)

blog.name: silkygoldmilkweed
blog.title: sansa stark & sandor clegane are soulmates

tags: a song of ice and fire
body:
Love vs Duty

Sansa gave up on love a while back. She has had her romantic notions literally beaten out of her. After {low point varies between book and show}, she is exclusively invested in the status of the Starks and the well-being of the North as a whole. In the show she pushes for the Battle of the Bastards, and then rejects the advances of both Dany and Tyrion in favor of a stern allegiance to the North. She ends us with a brother on the throne and he lets her separate from the Six Kingdoms.

Now, if this is her arc (and this theme is certain identified as crucial in Jon’s arc) it stands to reason that Sansa’s story should end with her alone.

What we saw in the show was Sansa in a Elizabeth I-like position. Alone and powerful because she was not bound to a man.

BUT damn it, what of heirs? Sansa is still incredibly young and presumably fertile. She could and should still have children. And given that she seems to dwell on the preeminence of House Stark and the reconstruction of Winterfell, one would imagine she wants heirs named Stark to carry on her family’s 8,000-year legacy.

So…I think this may be an aspect of the books left unfilmed, because the show is not the books.

Long story short, while I don’t know if Cleganebowl exists in the books or is fatal to the Hound, I think there is a chance that the Northman-looking huge guy who comes with a bunch of potency imagery (uncut Stranger/Driftwood) and perhaps a magical bond with the Starks might be a good candidate for heir-making.

In the books, on which I am definitely not foolishly pinning my hopes, I suspect the Hound may be the father of one or more bastards by Sansa Stark, legitimized at her leisure and named heir to the North. Whether or not he lives to meet them or is involved in their lives remains TBD.

Or maybe just everyone dies. Could go either way. Argh.

blog.name: funkymbtifiction
blog.title: Funky MBTI in Fiction
blog.description: Teaching MBTI and Enneagram through fictional characters.

summary: Do you still feel Sansa Stark is ISFJ? If yes, I’d love a more in depth analysis from season 8 on why you think so. If not, I’d...
question: Do you still feel Sansa Stark is ISFJ? If yes, I’d love a more in depth analysis from season 8 on why you think so. If not, I’d also love to know what you think she is now. Thank you for your time! I love your blog 💙
answer:
She’s SFJ, yes.

Zero Fi. No sense of personal identity or stakes. She thinks in terms of “us” – the Stark Family and the North. She has undertaken a mothering role to the North and sees herself as their collective representative (Fe). All of her wisdom about Dany and other threats are built up from watching deceitful, manipulative, brutal people rise and fall (Si). It’s not intuition, it’s her personal experiences. Her 3 core makes her very detached / become whatever the situation requires.

I’m indecisive on where her Ne and Ti falls. She might be ESFJ, given her sheer amount of Fe.

- ENFP Mod

summary: none of the starks are straight, a conspiracy thread
body:
none of the starks are straight, a conspiracy thread

  • ned: definitely had a “just guys bein dudes” thing with robert.
  • catelyn: you know when there’s someone you hate more than anything but also would maybe be dtf with? yeah, that’s cersei for her.
  • robb: followed in his father’s proud tradition of having a “just guys bein dudes” thing with theon.
  • jon: no straight man notices another man’s hair and skin as much as he does. jon and satin are boyfriends, it is known.
  • sansa: one day our sweet baby gay is gonna realize that the reason she likes all those songs about princesses and ladies is because of, well, the princesses and ladies.
  • arya: feels like she doesn’t fit in with the role society has given her and has a complicated relationship with gender presentation? baby girl is a butch in the making.
  • bran: definitely had crushes on both reed siblings.
  • rickon: too young to tell quite yet, but he seems like he’ll exude major Chaotic Bisexual™ vibes when he’s older.

bonus:

  • lyanna: all of the stark siblings had crushes on ashara dayne, no exceptions.
  • benjen: swearing yourself to an organization that doesn’t allow you to ever marry but puts you in the proximity of a bunch of other single dudes? doesn’t sound super straight to me.
  • brandon: okay i lied, brandon is the token straight person of the stark family. but everyone else is some shade of gay and that’s just facts.
